Childcare is one of the largest household expenses for families, often exceeding rent or tuition. When care is unaffordable, parents, especially mothers, may leave the workforce, deepening gender and income gaps. Affordable care is crucial for child development, economic mobility, and labor market participation.

The National Database of Childcare Prices (NDCP) includes cost estimates from over 3,000 U.S. counties between 2008 and 2018. It breaks down prices by care type (center-based vs. family-based), child age (infant, toddler, preschool), and percentile levels (median and 75th). Flags indicate data quality and estimation methods.
